```
using System.Numerics;

internal static class PopCountExtensionTest
{
    extension<TNumber>(TNumber number)
        where TNumber : IBinaryInteger<TNumber>
    {
        public TNumber PopCount => TNumber.PopCount(number);
    }

    public static void Test()
    {
        int n = 3;
        int c1 = n.PopCount; // error CS0428: Cannot convert method group 'PopCount' to non-delegate type 'int'. Did you intend to invoke the method?
        int c2 = n.PopCount(); // error CS7036: There is no argument given that corresponds to the required parameter 'value' of 'int.PopCount(int)'
        int c3 = n.PopCount(n); // error CS0176: Member 'int.PopCount(int)' cannot be accessed with an instance reference; qualify it with a type name instead
        int c4 = int.PopCount(n); // no error
    }
}
```
(The first error is the one that I care about.  The other two are expected.  However, the 2nd and 3rd errors were made by trying to follow the instructions in the previous error.)

**Expected Behavior**:
The compiler should resolve "n.PopCount" as the extension property when it is used on an integer.  (This should not resolve to the static method on int.)

**Actual Behavior**:
The compiler resolves "n.PopCount" as being the static method "int.PopCount(int n)".

